Dataset

  • URL: https://data.education.gouv.fr/explore/dataset/fr-en-college-effectifs-niveau-sexe-lv/

  • This dataset contains the number of students in middle schools by grade level, gender, main foreign languages (LV1), and second foreign languages (LV2), observed at the beginning of October each year.

  • Shape: 541 columns; 32,982 records

  • Period: From the start of the 2019 school year to the start of the 2022 school year (Last observation on 01/10/2022).

  • The data includes both public and private institutions under contract.

# Read the JSON file
with open('data/data_description.json', 'r') as file:
    schema = json.load(file)

# Initialize dictionaries to store variables by type
variables_by_type = {
    "string": [],
    "integer": [],
    "float": [],
    "boolean": [],
    "array": [],
    "object": []
}

# Recursive function to extract variables by type
def extract_variables(properties, prefix=""):
    for key, value in properties.items():
        var_type = value.get("type")
        if var_type:
            variables_by_type[var_type].append(prefix + key)
        # Check for nested objects
        if var_type == "object":
            extract_variables(value.get("properties", {}), prefix + key + ".")

# Extract properties from the JSON schema
fields_properties = schema["definitions"]["fr-en-college-effectifs-niveau-sexe-lv_records"]["properties"]["fields"]["properties"]
extract_variables(fields_properties)

# Display variables by type
for var_type, variables in variables_by_type.items():
    if variables:
        print(f"Variables of type {var_type}:")
        for variable in variables:
            print(f" - {variable}")
        print()

df = initial_df[['Numro du collge', "Nombre d'lves total", 
                 'Rgion', 'Secteur',
                 '6mes garons', '6mes filles',
                 '5mes garons', '5mes filles',
                 '4mes garons', '4mes filles',
                 '3mes garons', '3mes filles',
                ]].copy() 

#Girls

df['delta_6_5_F'] = df['5mes filles'] - df['6mes filles']
df['taux_6_5_F'] = df['delta_6_5_F'] / df['6mes filles']

df['delta_5_4_F'] = df['4mes filles'] - df['5mes filles']
df['taux_5_4_F'] = df['delta_5_4_F'] / df['5mes filles']

df['delta_4_3_F'] = df['3mes filles'] - df['4mes filles']
df['taux_4_3_F'] = df['delta_4_3_F'] / df['4mes filles']

df['DELTA_F'] = df['delta_6_5_F'] + df['delta_5_4_F'] + df['delta_4_3_F']
df['nb_F'] = (df['6mes filles'] + df['5mes filles'] + df['4mes filles'] + df['3mes filles'])

df['TAUX_F'] = df['DELTA_F'] / (df['nb_F'])
df['TAUX_F'] = df['TAUX_F'].fillna(0)

#---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- ---- -- #Symmetry

#Boys

df['delta_6_5_G'] = df['5mes garons'] - df['6mes garons']
df['taux_6_5_G'] = df['delta_6_5_G'] / df['6mes garons']

df['delta_5_4_G'] = df['4mes garons'] - df['5mes garons']
df['taux_5_4_G'] = df['delta_5_4_G'] / df['5mes garons']

df['delta_4_3_G'] = df['3mes garons'] - df['4mes garons']
df['taux_4_3_G'] = df['delta_4_3_G'] / df['4mes garons']

df['DELTA_G'] = df['delta_6_5_G'] + df['delta_5_4_G'] + df['delta_4_3_G']
df['nb_G'] = (df['6mes garons'] + df['5mes garons'] + df['4mes garons'] + df['3mes garons'])

df['TAUX_G'] = df['DELTA_G'] / df['nb_G']
df['TAUX_G'] = df['TAUX_G'].fillna(0)



df['TAUX'] = (df['DELTA_F'] + df['DELTA_G']) / ((df['nb_F']) + (df['nb_G']))

# Normality tests and descriptive statistics for 'TAUX', 'TAUX_G', and 'TAUX_F'
for name, data in zip(['TAUX', 'TAUX_G', 'TAUX_F'], [df['TAUX'], df['TAUX_G'], df['TAUX_F']]):
    shapiro_test = stats.shapiro(data[:5000])  # Shapiro-Wilk test with a subset
    ks_test = stats.kstest(data, 'norm')
    anderson_test = stats.anderson(data, dist='norm')
    jarque_bera_test = stats.jarque_bera(data)
    
    print(f"Normality test results for {name} :\n---------------------------------------------------------------------")
    print(f"Shapiro-Wilk test:"
          f"  Statistic: {shapiro_test.statistic:.4f}"
          f"  p-value: {shapiro_test.pvalue:.4f}\n")
    
    print(f"Kolmogorov-Smirnov test:"
          f"  Statistic: {ks_test.statistic:.4f}"
          f"  p-value: {ks_test.pvalue:.4f}\n")
    
    print(f"Anderson-Darling test:"
          f"  Statistic: {anderson_test.statistic:.4f}"
          f"  Critical values: {anderson_test.critical_values}"
          f"  Significance level: {anderson_test.significance_level}\n")
    
    print(f"Jarque-Bera test:"
          f"  Statistic: {jarque_bera_test.statistic:.4f}"
          f"  p-value: {jarque_bera_test.pvalue:.4f}\n")
    
    skewness = stats.skew(data)
    kurtosis = stats.kurtosis(data)
    
    print(f"Descriptive statistics for {name}:")
    print(f"Skewness: {skewness:.4f}")
    print(f"Kurtosis: {kurtosis:.4f}\n")

  • Based on the QQ-Plot and the various normality tests, we observe that the dropout rate distribution does not follow a normal distribution.
  • This could be explained by the fact that some middle schools cater to different needs (general education vs vocational education).
  • In the context of this study, we are focusing on all middle schools in France, which explains why our data is not normally distributed.

Questions

(1) Do some middle schools have more school dropouts than others? (Reduction in the number of students between 6th grade and 3rd grade)

(1.1) Kruskal-Wallis Test (difference between several groups - non-parametric)

(1.1.1) Assumptions
  • Response variable is ordinal or continuous: (OK)
  • Similar distribution: (OK)
(1.1.2) Results
In[31]:
data = [df[df["Numro du collge"] == college]['TAUX'] for college in df["Numro du collge"].unique()]     # Prparation des donnes
h_statistic, p_value = kruskal(*data)                                                                       # Test de Kruskal-Wallis

print(f"Kruskal-Wallis Test: H = {h_statistic}, p-value = {p_value}")

if p_value < 0.05:
    print("There is sufficient evidence to conclude that some colleges have higher dropout rates than others")
else:
    print("There is insufficient evidence to conclude that some colleges have higher dropout rates than others")

Kruskal-Wallis Test: H = 21288.252250142534, p-value = 0.0

# Pearson Correlation
pearson_corr, pearson_p_value = pearsonr(df["Nombre d'lves total"], df['TAUX'])
print(f"Pearson Correlation: {pearson_corr}, p-value: {pearson_p_value}")

if pearson_p_value < 0.05:
    if pearson_corr > 0:
        print("There is a significant positive correlation between college size and dropout rate (Pearson).\n")
    else:
        print("There is a significant negative correlation between college size and dropout rate (Pearson).\n")
else:
    print("No significant correlation was found between college size and dropout rate (Pearson).\n")

# Spearman Correlation
spearman_corr, spearman_p_value = spearmanr(df["Nombre d'lves total"], df['TAUX'])
print(f"Spearman Correlation: {spearman_corr}, p-value: {spearman_p_value}")     # Spearman Correlation

(4) Does the observation change depending on the region?

(4.1) Descriptive Statistics

  1. Description of data by region
    Descriptive statistics: Descriptive statistics (mean, median, standard deviation, etc.) of the variables of interest for each region.
    Visualization: Graphs such as boxplots or bar charts to visualize the differences between regions.

  2. Normality tests
    Check if the data is normally distributed in each region (Shapiro-Wilk test, Kolmogorov-Smirnov test, etc.).

  3. Comparison between regions
    ANOVA or Kruskal-Wallis: ANOVA (if the data is normal and variances are homogeneous) or the Kruskal-Wallis test (if the data is not normal).
    Post hoc tests: If the ANOVA or Kruskal-Wallis test shows significant differences, post hoc tests (such as Tukey for ANOVA or Dunn for Kruskal-Wallis) to identify which regions differ specifically from each other.
    Mann-Whitney U test: If only comparing two regions at a time and the data is not normally distributed, Mann-Whitney U test.

  4. Statistical models
    Two-way ANOVA
    Mixed models: To account for intra-regional and inter-regional variability, mixed-effects models.

(5) Is there a link between the dropout rate and whether the school is public or private?

(5.1) Mann-Whitney U Test (distribution difference between two samples - non-parametric)

In[40]:
# Separation of data by sector and gender
public_girls = df[df['Secteur'] == 'PUBLIC']['TAUX_F']
private_girls = df[df['Secteur'] == 'PRIVE']['TAUX_F']

public_boys = df[df['Secteur'] == 'PUBLIC']['TAUX_G']
private_boys = df[df['Secteur'] == 'PRIVE']['TAUX_G']

# Mann-Whitney U test for girls
stat_girls, p_girls = mannwhitneyu(public_girls.dropna(), private_girls.dropna())

# Mann-Whitney U test for boys
stat_boys, p_boys = mannwhitneyu(public_boys.dropna(), private_boys.dropna())

# Display results
print(f'Mann-Whitney U test for girls:')
print(f'Test statistic: {stat_girls}')
print(f'P-value: {p_girls}')

if p_girls < 0.05:
    print('The difference between girls in public and private schools is statistically significant.')
else:
    print('The difference between girls in public and private schools is not statistically significant.')

print('\nMann-Whitney U test for boys:')
print(f'Test statistic: {stat_boys}')
print(f'P-value: {p_boys}')

if p_boys < 0.05:
    print('The difference between boys in public and private schools is statistically significant.')
else:
    print('The difference between boys in public and private schools is not statistically significant.')
